06929nam a22010095i 9780231520300DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2008054884  a(OCoLC)979751706  a97802315203007 a10.7312/alle141462doi  a(DE-B1597)458590  a(OCoLC)785572692  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHV697b.D45 2009 7aSOC0160002bisacsh04a361.300aDelivering Home-Based Services :bA Social Work Perspective /ced. by Elizabeth Tracy, Susan Allen. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b6 tables, 1 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPart I. Introduction -- t1. Historical and Current Context -- t2. Ethical Issues and Guidelines -- t3. Administrative Supports and Practices -- t4. Social Policy Context -- tPart II. Home-Based Services in Social Work Fields of Practice -- t5. Early Childhood Programs -- t6. School-Based Services -- t7. Child Welfare -- t8. Child Mental Health -- t9. Criminal Justice -- t10. Adult Mental Health -- t11. Older Adult Services -- t12. Hospice and End-of-Life Care -- tPart III. Conclusion -- t13. Conclusions and Considerations for the Future -- tAppendix: Organizations Associated with Home-Based Programs, Research, or Policies -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aService providers are increasingly called upon to serve clients at home, a setting even a seasoned professional can find difficult to negotiate. From monitoring the health of older populations to managing paroled offenders, preventing child abuse, and reunifying families, home-based services require models that ensure positive outcomes and address the ethical dilemmas that might arise in such sensitive contexts.The contributors to this volume are national experts in diverse fields of social work practice, policy, and research. Treating the home as an ecological setting that guides human development and family interaction, they present rationales for and overviews of evidence-based models across an array of populations and fields of practice. Part 1 provides historical background and contemporary applications for home-based services, highlighting ethical, administrative, and supervision issues and summarizing the social policies that shape service delivery. Part 2 addresses home-based practice in such fields as child and adult mental health, school social work, and hospice care, detailing the particular population being treated, the policy and agency context, theories and empirical data, and practice guidelines. Part 3, the editors present a unifying framework and suggest future directions for home-based social work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHome care services. 0aHome-based family services. 0aSocial work with children. 0aSocial work with older people. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Services.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Kathryn Betts, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Susan F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Susan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aArmstrong, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAshford, José B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalaam, Maureen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBooththroyd, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBriar-Lawson, Katharine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBriar-Lawswson, Katharine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCahn, Katath